“Learning rate too slow”

Here:

ANN takes very small steps
Learning happens slowly

Because learning rate is small:

training is safe
but takes more time

Small Learning Rate = Slow Learning
------
Real-Life Example 

Walking down stairs:

taking tiny steps
safe
but very slow
=========

“Learning rate too fast”

Here:

ANN takes very large jumps
skips the target area

Meaning
Large Learning Rate = Unstable Learning

========

Real-Life Example 

Trying to stop at a point while running fast:

you cross the target
move back again
miss again

Same happens in ANN.

=============

| Term                | Meaning                   |
| ------------------- | ------------------------- |
| Gradient Descent    | Method to reduce error    |
| Learning Rate       | Step size during learning |
| Target Point        | Minimum loss/error        |
| Small Learning Rate | Slow but stable           |
| Large Learning Rate | Fast but unstable         |

==========








